8. Key Decisions and Their Rationale
OCSVM per user: Genuine‑only training; no impostor data needed for training.

RBF kernel: Non‑linear boundary required.

Per‑axis + MFCC + Multitaper features: Literature proves they improve authentication; they are now integrated.

LOUO tuning: Only honest way to select hyperparameters for per‑user models.

Median imputation in Phase 1 and tuning scripts: More robust than zero imputation.

Weighted consensus (50‑35‑15): Reflects relative importance: Boruta+SHAP > RF LOUO > Fisher.

FRR limit (30%) in tuning: Prevents model from becoming too lenient just to maximise TAR.

9. Known Issues & Warnings
train_session.py still uses np.nan_to_num (zero imputation). For consistency, it should eventually use median imputation (as done in all other scripts).

Global tuning script tune_global.py exists but is biased. Use only for quick exploration; never for final hyperparameter selection.

drop_cols must be identical between train_session.py and the tuning script. The tuning script imports SessionOCSVM from train_session, so it uses the same drop_cols automatically. However, if you change drop_cols in train_session.py, you must re‑run the tuning script.

All early‑return default dictionaries must be kept up‑to‑date when adding new features. The _all_fft_defaults() helper is the master for FFT‑related features. Other methods should have similarly comprehensive default dicts.

The DTW templates must exist in the templates/ folder before feature extraction. If missing, the pipeline will abort.

User list in train_session.py main() may differ from the actual users in features/v2/. Ensure the USER_ID list matches the CSV files present.

10. Step‑by‑Step Plan to Continue the Project
Run tune_louo_expanded.py with N_USERS=10 and DATA_DIR="./features/v2". This will take time but will yield reliable hyperparameters.

Apply the best hyperparameters to train_session.py (replace the hardcoded nu, gamma, threshold).

Uncomment extract_fused_touch_sensor_features and extract_jerk_smoothness_features in extract_session_features of the feature creation script, regenerate CSVs, and re‑run LOUO tuning to measure improvement.

Implement richer aggregation of spectral features (std, skew, p5, p95) in _extract_windowed_fft, _extract_mfcc_features, _extract_multitaper_features. Update default dictionaries. Regenerate CSVs and re‑tune.

Add remaining planned features (high‑frequency band, sample entropy, spectral coherence, per‑gesture statistics) one by one, each time regenerating CSVs and re‑running LOUO tuning to confirm TAR gain.

Compare the lead’s hand‑picked feature set against various top‑K consensus sets (K=30,50,70,90,100) by running the full grid search for each candidate set. The candidate set evaluation script grid_search_candidate.py needs to be created (or adapt tune_louo_expanded.py to accept a feature list CSV).

Lock the final feature set that achieves the highest TAR while respecting FAR and FRR limits.

If possible, set aside 4 users as a final held‑out set and evaluate the locked model on them to report an unbiased final performance.

11. Critical Assumptions
The label column in test CSVs uses 0 for genuine and 1 for impostor.

All training sessions are genuine.

The sensor sampling rate is roughly 16 Hz (auto‑detected).

The same set of features exists in all CSV files; any mismatch is handled by taking the intersection.

Impostor sessions are device‑specific and should never be pooled across users (each impostor session belongs to the device/user whose CSV it appears in).

The project does not currently use any data from the held‑out test users during feature selection or tuning.

